zshrc.local/.title: zshrc.local
zshrc.local/.body:
.zshrc.local
What's this?
This file is the source of my .zshrc.local file.
Add source ${HOME}/.zshrc.local in your .zshrc to activate it.
pyenv
export PYENV_ROOT="$HOME/.pyenv"
export PATH="$PYENV_ROOT/bin:$PATH"
eval "$(pyenv init -)"

rbenv
export RBENV_ROOT="$HOME/.rbenv"
export PATH="$RBENV_ROOT/bin:$PATH"
eval "$(rbenv init -)"

nodenv
export NODENV_ROOT="$HOME/.nodenv"
export PATH="$NODENV_ROOT/bin:$PATH"
eval "$(nodenv init -)"

Golang
export PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/go/bin:$HOME/r/bin
export GOPATH=$HOME/r

Vim
alias v='vim $(fzf)'
alias vdotfiles='pushd ~/dotfiles > /dev/null; vim README.md; popd > /dev/null'
alias vtil='pushd ~/til > /dev/null; vim README.md; popd > /dev/null'

Bookmark
bm to bookmark the current working directory.
alias bm='echo "${PWD}" >> ~/.bookmarks'

cdb to list bookmarks and move to one of them.
alias cdb='cd $(cat ~/.bookmarks | sort | uniq | sed -e "/^#/d" | sed -e "/^\s*$/d" | fzf)'

vbm to start vim to edit the bookmarks.
alias vbm='vim ~/.bookmarks'

Git
cdg to move repositories managed in GOPATH.
alias cdg='cd "${GOPATH}/src"/$(find ${GOPATH}/src -maxdepth 3 -mindepth 3 -type d | sed -re "s/^.*?\/(.*\/.*\/.*)$/\1/g" | fzf)'

fbr to list and switch branches.
fbr() {
  local branches branch
  branches=$(git branch -vv) &&
  branch=$(echo "$branches" | fzf +m) &&
  git checkout $(echo "$branch" | awk '{print $1}' | sed "s/.* //")
}

Misc
Deactivate screen lock (C-s)
stty ixany

Change key bindings with xmodmap
xmodmap ~/.Xmodmap

What's this?
This file is the source of my .vimrc file.
Prerequisite
Vim 8
I recently started to use Vim 8 and found it super!!
Here's the script to install it in Ubuntu 16.04
sudo add-apt-repository ppa:jonathonf/vim
sudo apt update
sudo apt install vim
sudo apt install ppa-purge && sudo ppa-purge ppa:jonathonf/vim

The script above is copied from 
http://tipsonubuntu.com/2016/09/13/vim-8-0-released-install-ubuntu-16-04/
vim-plug
This .vimrc uses vim-plug to install vim plugins so that I need to run the following command in advance.
curl -fLo ~/.vim/autoload/plug.vim --create-dirs \
    https://raw.githubusercontent.com/junegunn/vim-plug/master/plug.vim

Python 3.5 and neovim
neovim, whichi is the Python module of vim client, is required by deoplete plugin.
Python 3.5 is registerted in apt packages.
sudo apt-get install python3 python3-pip

neovim is installable by pip or pip3 command.
sudo pip3 install neovim

I tried to use Python installed by pyenv at first but gave up after several minutes struggling.
I uses the default system Python now.
fzf
fzf is a command-line fuzzy finder which is available from vim with its vim plugin.
fzf is easy to install with go get command (as far as you've installed go)
go get github.com/junegunn/fzf

General
Use spaces instead of tab.
set expandtab

Show 2 spaces for each tab.
This conf is useful especially when I write Golang.
set tabstop=2

Use 2 spaces for each indent.
set shiftwidth=2

Show line numbers.
set number

Save files automatically.
set autowrite

In Tab typed, show the list of matches and complete the longest common part.
In Tab tabyped again, select the first match, the second match etc. 
set wildmenu
set wildmode=list:longest,full

Assign Space key to the leader key.
let mapleader = "\"

Toggle NERDTree with F8.
nmap  :NERDTreeToggle

Highlight matched texts.
set hlsearch

Activate incremental search.
set incsearch

Ignore the difference of cases until I use both lower/upper case characters in search.
set ignorecase
set smartcase

Switch buffers with 
nnoremap  :bn
nnoremap  :bp

Disable swp file
set noswapfile

Plugins
Let vim-plug install the plugins in ~/.vim/plugged.
call plug#begin('~/.vim/plugged')

Markdown
Plugins to edit Markdown.
https://github.com/plasticboy/vim-markdown
Plug 'godlygeek/tabular'
Plug 'plasticboy/vim-markdown'

Plugin to generate TOC of a markdown file.
https://github.com/mzlogin/vim-markdown-toc
Plug 'mzlogin/vim-markdown-toc'

YAML
Plugin to edit YAML files.
Plug 'stephpy/vim-yaml'

NERDTree
https://github.com/scrooloose/nerdtree
Plug 'scrooloose/nerdtree'

fzf

https://github.com/junegunn/fzf/blob/master/README-VIM.md
https://github.com/junegunn/fzf.vim

Plug 'junegunn/fzf'
Plug 'junegunn/fzf.vim'

Deoplete (Auto complete)
I love Deoplete!!
if has('nvim')
  Plug 'Shougo/deoplete.nvim', { 'do': ':UpdateRemotePlugins' }
else
  Plug 'Shougo/deoplete.nvim'
  Plug 'roxma/nvim-yarp'
  Plug 'roxma/vim-hug-neovim-rpc'
endif

let g:deoplete#enable_at_startup = 1

Golang
Plugins to edit golang.
vim-go integrates vim with Golang toolkits such as gofmt, errcheck etc.
Plug 'fatih/vim-go', { 'do': ':GoInstallBinaries' }

vim-go's tutorial in Japanese is here. https://github.com/hnakamur/vim-go-tutorial-ja
deoplete's plugin for Golang.
https://github.com/zchee/deoplete-go
Plug 'zchee/deoplete-go', { 'do': 'make'}

Ruby
Plugins to edit Ruby.
vim-ruby's document is here. https://github.com/vim-ruby/vim-ruby/wiki 
Plug 'vim-ruby/vim-ruby'

deoplete's plugin for Ruby.
https://github.com/fishbullet/deoplete-ruby
Plug 'fishbullet/deoplete-ruby'

Plugin to run rspec via vim.
https://github.com/thoughtbot/vim-rspec
Plug 'thoughtbot/vim-rspec'

augroup rb_augroup
  autocmd!
  autocmd FileType ruby nmap t :call RunAllSpecs()
  autocmd FileType ruby nmap tt :call RunCurrentSpecFile()
  autocmd FileType ruby nmap tl :call RunLastSpec()
  autocmd FileType ruby nmap tn :call RunNearestSpec()
augroup END

Plugin for Rails projects.
Plug 'tpope/vim-rails'

PlantUML
https://github.com/aklt/plantuml-syntax
Plug 'aklt/plantuml-syntax'

let g:plantuml_executable_script="java -jar $HOME/bin/plantuml.jar -tsvg"

Initialize vim-plug
Let vim-plug initialzie itself with the plugins above.
call plug#end()

Now that I can install/update the plugins with :PluginInstall command.
Look and feel
Fzf
Run Files with e.
augroup fzf_augroup
  autocmd!
  noremap e :Files
augroup END

Markdown
augroup md_augroup
  autocmd!
  " Disable folding.
  autocmd FileType markdown set nofoldenable
augroup END

Enable TOC window auto-fit.
let g:vim_markdown_toc_autofit = 1

Follow named anchors.
let g:vim_markdown_follow_anchor = 1

Golang
augroup go_augroup
  autocmd!
  " Use tab
  autocmd FileType go set noexpandtab
  autocmd FileType go nmap b  (go-build)
  autocmd FileType go nmap r  (go-run)
  autocmd FileType go nmap t  (go-test)
  autocmd FileType go nmap n  :cnext
  autocmd FileType go nmap p  :cprevious
augroup END

Tips
Links in this section might include pages in Japanese.
Keybindings

http://vim-jp.org/vimdoc-ja/map.html
https://cocopon.me/blog/2013/10/vim-map-noremap/

How to check the filetype of the opened file.
verbose set filetype?

tmux.conf/.title: tmuxrc.conf
tmux.conf/.body:
.tmux.conf


Swich prefix key
Open a window/pane with F2
Switch windows with F3 and F4
Switch panes with M-arrow
Resize panes with M-S-arrow
Start copy-mode with F7


Swich prefix key
Cancel keybindings for C-b, the default.
unbind C-b

Use C-q as the prefix key.
set -g prefix C-q

Open a window/pane with F2

F2: open a new window.
S-F2: split the current window horizontally and open a new pane.
C-F2: split the current window vertically and open a new pane.

bind-key -n F2 new-window -c "#{pane_current_path}" \; rename-window "-"

bind-key -n C-F2 display-panes \; split-window -h -c "#{pane_current_path}"
bind-key -n S-F2 display-panes \; split-window -v -c "#{pane_current_path}"

Switch windows with F3 and F4
bind-key -n F3 previous-window
bind-key -n F4 next-window

Switch panes with M-arrow
bind-key -n M-Up display-panes \; select-pane -U
bind-key -n M-Down display-panes \; select-pane -D
bind-key -n M-Left display-panes \; select-pane -L
bind-key -n M-Right display-panes \; select-pane -R

Resize panes with M-S-arrow
bind-key -n M-S-Up resize-pane -U
bind-key -n M-S-Down resize-pane -D
bind-key -n M-S-Left resize-pane -L
bind-key -n M-S-Right resize-pane -R

Start copy-mode with F7
bind-key -n F7 copy-mode

Xmodmap/.title: Xmodmap
Xmodmap/.body:
.Xmodmap
What's this?
Configuration
Regard Henkan as Escape
keycode 100 = Escape

Regard Muhenkan and Kana keys as Space
keycode 101 = space
keycode 102 = space

How to check the keycode.
Use xev command.
xev command opens a small window which captures and dumps all the occurred events including KeyPress events each of which has keycode property.
You can see logs like below when you type Space key.
KeyPress event, serial 37, synthetic NO, window 0x3c00001,
  ...
  state 0x0, keycode 65 (keysym 0x20, space), same_screen YES,
  ...
The log says that the keycode of Space key is 65.
How to check the current keycode mapping
xmodmap -pke

Tips

http://bearmini.hatenablog.com/entry/2013/07/12/161637
